Latini, -orum, m. : av. Latium.

Latinus, -i, m. : sm. Aeneas.

Latium. -ii, n. : the country of the Latini, lying on the west coast of Italy, between the Tiber and the Sabines on the north, the Marsi and Samnium on the east, Campania on the south-east, and the sea. In the time of the kings this region was divided amongst several small tribes, such as the Aequi, Hernici, Volsci (q.v.), and the Prisci Latini, Aborigines, or Old Latins. The latter occupied thirty cities in the immediate neighbourhood of Rome, chief amongst which was Alba Longa. After Alba was rased by Tullus Hostilius, the Latini were gradually reduced by successive kings, until the expulsion of Tarquin the Arrogant gave them the opportunity of throwing off thc yoke of Rome. They were finally conq uered at the close of the Latin War, 338 B.c., and many of their towns received the full civitas, or franchise, of Rome. The remainder became allied towns (socii), with certain special privileges, and were known as the Nomen Latinum, in which, however, were included many other colonies of Rome outside Latium.
